  "response": "When you swallow phlegm, it goes down your esophagus and into your stomach. Here's what happens:\n\n*   **Stomach Acid:** Your stomach acid is extremely acidic. It breaks down the proteins and other components of the phlegm, just like it does with the food you eat.\n\n*   **Digestion:** The broken-down components are then further digested and absorbed by your intestines, along with the rest of your food.\n\n*   **Waste:** Any undigested remnants are eventually eliminated from your body as part of your feces.\n\n**In short, swallowing phlegm is generally harmless.** Your body is designed to handle it. The only real risk is the potential for reinfection if the phlegm contains active pathogens (like bacteria or viruses). But even then, stomach acid usually takes care of it.\n",
